1
00:02:34,971 --> 00:02:36,939
Hello, stranger.

2
00:03:12,108 --> 00:03:14,338
Sorry. Looking for a cigarette.

3
00:03:15,244 --> 00:03:16,575
I've given up.

4
00:03:19,282 --> 00:03:20,647
Thank you.

5
00:03:22,986 --> 00:03:25,216
- Got to be somewhere?
- Work.

6
00:03:26,756 --> 00:03:28,747
You didn't fancy my sandwiches?

7
00:03:28,858 --> 00:03:31,486
- Don't eat fish.
- Why not?

8
00:03:32,362 --> 00:03:34,057
Fish piss in the sea.

9
00:03:34,564 --> 00:03:37,397
- So do children.
- Don't eat children, either.

10
00:03:38,701 --> 00:03:40,191
What's your work?

11
00:03:40,269 --> 00:03:42,430
I'm sort of a journalist.

12
00:03:42,772 --> 00:03:45,605
- What sort?
- I write obituaries.

13
00:03:57,587 --> 00:03:59,748
Are we in for a long wait?

14
00:04:01,858 --> 00:04:03,985
She was 21 when she came in.

15
00:04:06,362 --> 00:04:07,852
Does it hurt?

16
00:04:08,564 --> 00:04:09,895
I'll live.

17
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,468
Do you want me to put your leg up?

18
00:04:13,536 --> 00:04:15,094
Yes, please.

19
00:04:29,919 --> 00:04:31,910
Who cut off your crusts?

20
00:04:32,355 --> 00:04:33,344
Me.

21
00:04:33,423 --> 00:04:36,358
Did your mother cut off your crusts
when you were a little boy?

22
00:04:36,426 --> 00:04:39,793
- Yes, I believe she did.
- You should eat your crusts.

23
00:04:40,163 --> 00:04:42,063
You should stop smoking.

24
00:04:43,599 --> 00:04:45,089
How long was I out?

25
00:04:45,168 --> 00:04:47,728
- About 10 seconds.
- Then what?

26
00:04:49,005 --> 00:04:50,996
You came to. You focused on me.

27
00:04:51,074 --> 00:04:53,770
You said, "Hello, stranger."

28
00:04:53,843 --> 00:04:55,401
What a floozy.

29
00:04:55,478 --> 00:04:59,312
The cabbie crossed himself, he went,
"Thank fuck. I thought I'd killed her."

30
00:04:59,382 --> 00:05:01,748
I said, "Let's get her to a hospital."
He hesitated.

31
00:05:01,818 --> 00:05:05,117
I think he thought there'd be paperwork
and he'd be held responsible.

32
00:05:05,188 --> 00:05:08,646
So I said with a slight sneer,
"Please just drop us at the hospital."

33
00:05:08,724 --> 00:05:10,316
Show me the sneer.

34
00:05:11,260 --> 00:05:13,228
Very good, buster.

35
00:05:14,297 --> 00:05:15,787
Thank you.

36
00:05:24,574 --> 00:05:26,838
- I told you, I've given up.
- Try harder.

37
00:05:26,909 --> 00:05:28,467
You live here?

38
00:05:28,878 --> 00:05:31,073
Just arrived from New York.

39
00:05:31,781 --> 00:05:33,715
Taking a vacation?

40
00:05:33,783 --> 00:05:35,683
I'm on an expedition.

41
00:05:36,319 --> 00:05:38,116
Where's your baggage?

42
00:05:39,255 --> 00:05:41,985
- Where are you staying?
- I'm a waif.

43
00:05:44,627 --> 00:05:46,117
A red bus.

44
00:05:47,864 --> 00:05:52,198
Policeman or "bobby."
Observe the distinctive helmet.

45
00:05:53,836 --> 00:05:56,361
Saint Paul's Cathedral.
Please note the famous dome.

46
00:05:56,439 --> 00:06:00,273
- This is a truly magnificent tour.
- It's the London tourists never get to see.

47
00:06:00,343 --> 00:06:03,176
- What's this?
- I've no idea.

48
00:06:23,933 --> 00:06:27,699
They're all people
who died saving the lives of others.

49
00:06:29,372 --> 00:06:31,272
I've been here before.

50
00:06:40,883 --> 00:06:43,716
Twenty years ago, we came here.

51
00:06:44,954 --> 00:06:48,947
My mother's dead. My father and I came here
the afternoon she died.

52
00:06:50,693 --> 00:06:54,390
She was a smoker.
She died in the hospital, actually.

53
00:06:54,463 --> 00:06:57,193
- Is your father still alive?
- Hanging on.

54
00:06:57,633 --> 00:06:58,930
He's in a home.

55
00:06:59,569 --> 00:07:02,834
- You're late for work.
- You saying you want me to go?

56
00:07:02,905 --> 00:07:04,805
I'm saying you're late for work.

57
00:07:05,508 --> 00:07:08,068
How did you end up writing obituaries?

58
00:07:08,377 --> 00:07:12,507
Well, I had dreams of being a writer,
but I had no voice.

59
00:07:13,149 --> 00:07:15,515
What am I saying? I had no talent.

60
00:07:15,585 --> 00:07:19,851
So I ended up in obituaries,
which is the Siberia of journalism.

61
00:07:20,089 --> 00:07:23,786
Tell me what you do.
I want to imagine you in Siberia.

62
00:07:23,859 --> 00:07:25,190
Really?

63
00:07:28,097 --> 00:07:30,930
We call it "the obits page."

64
00:07:31,968 --> 00:07:34,801
There's three of us: Me, Graham, and Harry.

65
00:07:35,404 --> 00:07:39,534
When I get to work, without fail...
Are you sure you want to know?

66
00:07:40,576 --> 00:07:44,672
Well, if someone important died,
we go to the "deep freeze"...

67
00:07:48,150 --> 00:07:51,677
which is a computer file...

68
00:07:51,754 --> 00:07:55,019
with all the obituaries,
and we find the dead person's life.

69
00:07:55,091 --> 00:07:57,753
People's obituaries are written
while they're still alive?

70
00:07:57,827 --> 00:07:59,419
Some people's.

71
00:07:59,996 --> 00:08:03,056
Then Harry, he's the editor,
decides who we'll lead with.

72
00:08:03,132 --> 00:08:05,327
Then we make calls, check facts.

73
00:08:05,401 --> 00:08:09,963
At 6:00, we stand around the computer
and look at the next day's page...

74
00:08:10,773 --> 00:08:13,071
and make final changes.

75
00:08:13,409 --> 00:08:16,207
Add a few euphemisms
for our own amusement.

76
00:08:16,279 --> 00:08:17,610
Such as?

77
00:08:19,882 --> 00:08:24,080
"He was a convivial fellow."
Meaning he was an alcoholic.

78
00:08:24,854 --> 00:08:28,255
"He valued his privacy." Gay.

79
00:08:28,724 --> 00:08:31,488
"He enjoyed his privacy." Raging queen.

80
00:08:32,695 --> 00:08:34,754
What would my euphemism be?

81
00:08:35,731 --> 00:08:38,723
- "She was disarming."
- That's not a euphemism.

82
00:08:39,602 --> 00:08:41,092
Yes, it is.

83
00:08:50,112 --> 00:08:53,013
- What were you doing in New York?
- You know.

84
00:08:56,152 --> 00:09:00,555
Well, no, I don't. What, were you studying?

85
00:09:00,723 --> 00:09:02,020
Stripping.

86
00:09:03,492 --> 00:09:05,722
Look at your little eyes.

87
00:09:06,829 --> 00:09:08,694
I can't see my little eyes.

88
00:09:14,136 --> 00:09:15,626
Why did you leave?

89
00:09:16,238 --> 00:09:18,229
Problems with a male.

90
00:09:18,507 --> 00:09:20,168
- Boyfriend?
- Kind of.

91
00:09:21,344 --> 00:09:23,574
And you left him, just like that?

92
00:09:23,646 --> 00:09:27,673
It's the only way to leave.
"I don't love you anymore. Goodbye."

93
00:09:27,750 --> 00:09:30,947
- Supposing you do still love them?
- You don't leave.

94
00:09:31,787 --> 00:09:34,950
- You've never left somebody you still love?
- No.

95
00:09:38,861 --> 00:09:40,419
This is me.

96
00:09:46,836 --> 00:09:48,497
Enjoy your stay.

97
00:09:49,839 --> 00:09:53,002
Please remember
our traffic tends to come from the right.

98
00:09:54,777 --> 00:09:55,869
Bye.

99
00:10:08,691 --> 00:10:10,591
Do you have a girlfriend?

100
00:10:10,960 --> 00:10:12,291
Yeah. Ruth.

101
00:10:12,862 --> 00:10:15,831
She's called Ruth. She's a linguist.

102
00:10:17,233 --> 00:10:19,394
- What's your name?
- Alice.

103
00:10:20,536 --> 00:10:22,970
My name is Alice Ayres.

104
00:10:29,979 --> 00:10:31,139
Good.

105
00:10:31,247 --> 00:10:34,410
I'm just gonna change the film.
Are you okay for time?

106
00:10:38,554 --> 00:10:41,216
- Do you mind if I smoke?
- Lf you must.

107
00:10:42,391 --> 00:10:44,916
- I don't have to.
- Then don't.

108
00:10:57,039 --> 00:10:58,734
I liked your book.

109
00:10:59,642 --> 00:11:00,802
Thanks.

110
00:11:02,711 --> 00:11:05,612
- When's it published?
- Next year. How come you've read it?

111
00:11:05,681 --> 00:11:08,912
Your publisher sent me a manuscript.
I read it last night.

112
00:11:09,518 --> 00:11:11,452
You kept me up till 4:00.

113
00:11:12,488 --> 00:11:13,750
I'm flattered.

114
00:11:14,123 --> 00:11:16,591
Is your heroine
based on someone you know?

115
00:11:17,159 --> 00:11:19,320
Yes. She's someone called Alice.

116
00:11:19,829 --> 00:11:22,320
How does she feel
about you stealing her life?

117
